T","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Joan de Hobrugg was born in 1215, in Essex, England, United Kingdom, her father, William Hobrugge, was 25 and her mother, Agnes Picot, was 21. She married Roger de Huntingfield in February 1236. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died on 7 September 1297, in Huntingfield with Cookley, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 82."},"et":{"1215–7 September 1297":"1215–7. september 1297","1213–Female":"1213–Surnud","1215–1297":"1215–1297","1195–1257":"1195–1257","1237–1290":"1237–1290","1190–1229":"1190–1229","1194–1233":"1194–1233","1190":"1190","Bef 2 November 1290":"enne 2. novembrit 1290","7 September 1297":"7. september 1297","1297":"1297","1195":"1195","1194":"1194","1236 (2nd wife)":"veebruar 1236","1290":"1290","1215":"1215","1237":"1237","24 August 1237":"24. august 1237","1257":"1257","1213":"1213","1233":"1233","9. Juli 1229":"9. juuli 1229","10 July 1257":"10. juuli 1257","1229":"1229","Huntingfield, Blything, Suffolk, England":"Huntingfield with Cookley, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Howbridge, Witham Essex, England":"Witham, Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Howbridge In Witham, Essex, England":"Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Howbridge, Witham, Essex, England":"Witham, Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1215–7 September 1297":"1215–7. syyskuuta 1297","1213–Female":"1213–Kuollut","1215–1297":"1215–1297","1195–1257":"1195–1257","1237–1290":"1237–1290","1190–1229":"1190–1229","1194–1233":"1194–1233","1190":"11